CSS SELECTOR:

We are not just limited to name, class name, tagname, linktext, partial link text, id
We are able to create custom locators with CSS Selector and Xpath
With CSS Selector We can use any attribute inside of the tag

Syntax:
tagname[attribute='value']

Example:
<a href="https://www.tesla.com" class="kk99" id="uh7" name="bb95"> TESLA <a/>

a[id='uh7']
a[name='bb95']

# stands for id attribute
. stands for class attribute

tagname#idvalue
tagname.classvalue

a#uh7 -- locates the weblement from idValue
a.kk99 -- locates the webelement from classValue

or

If you want to be less specific
#idValue
.classValue


How to move from parent to child (with greater(>) mark)

Syntax:
tagName[attribute='value'] > childTagName


Why do we need to go from parent to child?
Sometimes the weblement that we want to locate does not have a unique attribute

Example:
hashcontent>div>h2
.className>h2

Important:
We can not go from child to parent using CSS Selector

